  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Developing Server Architecture**\n\nI\'m making great headway on the server-side code. Currently, I\'m focusing on the `server.ts` implementation for the AI Care Concierge API. I\'m double-checking the Express + Vite middleware pattern from our framework instructions to ensure I get it right, particularly for handling static files during development and production. It\'s brilliant.\n\n\n**Refining Chat API**\n\nI\'m now diving into the `/api/chat` POST endpoint. I\'ve decided to format the chat history directly for `ai.models.generateContent`, keeping it straightforward. The structure of the `contents` argument is something I am focused on now. I\'m considering best practices to ensure clear message formatting.\n\n\n**Confirming Message Structure**\n\nI\'ve confirmed the message structure for `ai.models.generateContent` which includes `role` and `parts`. I am now leaning towards using this format. The standard Gemini content payload looks good. I\'m focusing on incorporating a system instruction from the configuration, for the AI Care Concierge. I\'m crafting a system instruction to simulate a compassionate, expert senior care advisor named Sarah at GoldenCare.\n\n\n**Defining System Instruction**\n\nI\'m now integrating GoldenCare\'s key details into the system instruction for the AI. It\'s critical to provide concrete examples and differentiate care types (Assisted Living, Memory Care, Independent Living) to give personalized recommendations. I\'m focusing on gently prompting for the user\'s loved one\'s needs to tailor responses. I also made sure to handle missing API keys.\n\n\n**Implementing Lazy Initialization**\n\nI\'ve got a crucial update: I\'m focusing on handling missing API keys gracefully. I\'m implementing lazy initialization for the `GoogleGenAI` client to prevent crashing the server on startup. This is essential! I\'m now writing the helper function to initialize the AI client only when first needed, which means avoiding unhandled exceptions. I will return a mock response or helpful instruction if the API key isn\'t set, instead of throwing an unhandled exception.\n\n\n**Designing Backup Responses**\n\nI\'ve got a fantastic new idea: if the API key is missing, I\'ll provide a compassionate, pre-programmed rule-based fallback. This ensures the chatbot remains operational in development and presents an elegant warning in the logs. Now I am designing those rule-based responses; for example, if the user asks about \"assisted living,\" it will return a specific answer.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the backend Express server at `/server.ts`. It includes a secure, lazy-initialized `/api/chat` route using the `@google/genai` SDK and handles static/Vite middleware for development and production modes. It gracefully handles cases where the Gemini API key is missing."
    thinking_duration {
